 According to a media statement released on June 11, Premier Refilwe Mtshweni-Tsipane was disappointed to find that a fake email account had been created in her name. Messages asking people for money were allegedly doing the rounds. ALSO SEE: IN PHOTOS: First day Kruger National Park sightings The Office of the Premier was alerted to this when several enquiries were made about the authenticity of the emails. An example of one of the emails sent from the fake account. The premier has since reported the matter to the South African Police Services. “I appeal to anyone who has received such an email to contact the police. People must not respond or give these scammers any money as I do not send anyone emails asking for anything,” said Mtshweni-Tsipane. ALSO READ: SANParks opens for self-drive day excursions after two months A case of fraud is currently being investigated.